TITLE: Crop-Wise Production Trends (2021-26)
The dashboard presents comprehensive production data across all major crop categories for the period 2021-26, enabling trend analysis and regional specialization assessment.

TITLE: Oilseed Production in India
Key Points
Groundnut has the highest production among oilseed crops, making it the most important oilseed in India

Soybean is the second-largest oilseed, showing its growing importance in edible oil and protein markets

Rapeseed & Mustard rank third and are mainly grown in northern and central India

Castor seed and Sesame have moderate production levels

Sunflower, Linseed, Safflower, and Nigerseed contribute very small shares, indicating limited cultivation

India's oilseed production is highly concentrated in a few major crops, rather than evenly distributed

This concentration increases dependence on imports for edible oils

State-wise Groundnut Production – Key Observations
Gujarat is the largest producer of groundnut in India, contributing the maximum share among all states

Rajasthan ranks second, but its production is significantly lower than Gujarat, showing Gujarat's dominance

Madhya Pradesh stands at third position, contributing a moderate amount

Tamil Nadu has noticeable but smaller production compared to the top three states

Uttar Pradesh, Maharashtra, Karnataka, and Andhra Pradesh show comparatively low groundnut production

Groundnut production in India is highly concentrated in western and central states

The large gap between Gujarat and other states indicates regional specialization in oilseed cultivation

TITLE: Top Food Grain Production by Crop (India)
Crop-wise Observations
a. Rice is the most produced food grain in India, showing its dominance as the primary staple crop
b. Wheat ranks second, reflecting its importance in northern and central India
c. Maize occupies the third position, indicating its growing demand for food, fodder, and industrial use
d. Jowar and Bajra show moderate production, mainly grown in semi-arid regions
e. Ragi has comparatively lower production but remains important for nutrition
f. Barley and small millets contribute the least, indicating limited cultivation area
g. Food grain production in India is highly concentrated in rice and wheat, which together form the majority share

State-wise Rice Production – Key Insights
Uttar Pradesh is the largest producer of rice, benefiting from extensive irrigation and large cultivated area

Punjab ranks second, with high productivity due to modern agricultural practices

West Bengal holds the third position because of favorable climate and rainfall

Madhya Pradesh and Telangana show almost equal rice production, indicating expansion in rice cultivation

Chhattisgarh and Odisha are important rice-growing states in eastern India

Bihar, Haryana, and Andhra Pradesh contribute comparatively lower rice production among the listed states

Rice production shows regional concentration, influenced by water availability and climatic conditions

TITLE: Pulses Production Distribution in India (by Crop)
Key Observations
Gram is the largest contributor to pulse production, accounting for about 40% of total output

Other pulses form the second-largest share with around 22%, showing the diversity of pulse cultivation

Tur (Arhar) contributes about 16%, making it the third most important pulse crop

Urad (Black gram) accounts for around 8–9% of total pulse production

Moong (Green gram) contributes nearly 8%, showing moderate production

Lentil has the smallest share, contributing less than 5%

Pulse production in India is dominated by a few major crops, especially gram and tur

TITLE: Top Commercial Crop Production by Crop (India)
Crop-wise Observations
a. Sugarcane dominates commercial crop production, contributing about 88% of the total output
b. Cotton is the second-largest commercial crop, but its share is much smaller than sugarcane
c. Jute & Mesta together account for around 5–6%, showing moderate contribution
d. Jute and Mesta individually have relatively small shares in overall production
e. Guarseed, Tobacco, and Sannhemp contribute negligible amounts, indicating very limited cultivation
f. Commercial crop production in India is highly concentrated in sugarcane
g. This concentration makes the sector sensitive to water availability and pricing policies

State-wise Commercial Crop Production – Key Observations
Uttar Pradesh is the largest producer of commercial crops, contributing about 50% of the total among selected states

Maharashtra ranks second with nearly 30%, driven mainly by sugarcane cultivation

Karnataka contributes around 12–13%, showing moderate commercial crop production

Gujarat has a smaller but notable share

Bihar and Tamil Nadu contribute the least, indicating limited commercial crop dominance

Commercial crop production is highly concentrated in a few states, especially Uttar Pradesh and Maharashtra

Regional dominance is influenced by climate, irrigation facilities, and sugar industry presence

TITLE: Spatial Distribution of Agricultural Production in India
Map-based Analysis – Key Observations
a. The map shows wide spatial variation in agricultural production across Indian states, indicating regional specialization
b. Northern states such as Uttar Pradesh, Punjab, and Haryana exhibit high agricultural activity, largely due to fertile alluvial soils and extensive irrigation
c. Central India, including Madhya Pradesh and Chhattisgarh, shows significant agricultural presence, contributing majorly to food grains and pulses
d. Western states like Maharashtra and Gujarat play an important role, especially in cash crops and oilseeds
e. Southern states such as Andhra Pradesh, Telangana, Tamil Nadu, and Karnataka display strong agricultural output supported by irrigation projects and diversified cropping patterns
f. Eastern India (West Bengal, Odisha, Bihar, Assam) is prominently involved in rice and jute cultivation, benefiting from high rainfall
g. North-Eastern states show comparatively smaller agricultural output, reflecting hilly terrain and limited cultivable land
h. Coastal and island regions (Goa, Andaman & Nicobar Islands) have lower production intensity due to geographical constraints
i. The size of markers indicates that agricultural production in India is not evenly distributed, but concentrated in a few major states
j. Overall, the map highlights how climate, soil type, irrigation, and land availability shape agricultural production across India

TITLE: Key Findings and Strategic Insights
Production Concentration Patterns
Crop-wise Concentration: India's agricultural output is concentrated in a few major crops:

Rice and Wheat dominate food grains (~70% of production)

Sugarcane dominates commercial crops (~88% of production)

Groundnut leads oilseeds

Gram dominates pulses (~40% of production)

Regional Concentration: Production is highly geographically concentrated:

North: Wheat, rice, sugarcane production centers

South: Rice, spices, commercial crops

West: Oilseeds (groundnut), cotton

East: Rice and jute

Water and Climate Dependency: Agricultural patterns are heavily influenced by:

Monsoon patterns and rainfall

Irrigation infrastructure availability

Soil fertility and type

Regional climate zones

